# =============================================================================
# B2B CONTACT & COMPANY DATA
# =============================================================================
CATEGORY_CONTENT["b2b-contact-data"] = {
 "definition": "provide verified contact information, including emails, direct dials, mobile numbers, and job titles, alongside company firmographics like revenue, headcount, industry, and tech stack. These databases are the foundation of outbound sales, giving reps the raw material they need to build targeted prospect lists.",
 "definition_expanded": "B2B data platforms aggregate professional contact records from public filings, web scraping, data partnerships, and contributor networks. The best providers verify records continuously, flagging job changes, bounced emails, and disconnected numbers. Accuracy varies significantly between vendors, especially for phone numbers and European contacts. Choosing the right provider depends on your target market, budget, and how much you value phone data versus email-only coverage.",
 "buying_guide": "Start with your ICP. If you sell to North American mid-market and enterprise companies, most major providers will have strong coverage. If your targets are SMBs, European companies, or niche verticals like healthcare or manufacturing, test accuracy on a sample of 200-300 target accounts before signing a contract. Coverage gaps in your specific market matter more than total database size.\n\nPhone number accuracy is the biggest differentiator between providers. Email verification rates cluster between 90-97% across top vendors, but direct dial accuracy ranges from 40% to 80%. If your sales motion depends on cold calling, prioritize providers with strong phone data and test connection rates yourself. If you run email-only outbound, you can save significantly by choosing a lower-cost provider with solid email verification.\n\nWatch the contract structure. Enterprise providers like ZoomInfo lock you into annual contracts with auto-renewal clauses and credit-based usage limits. Exceeding your credit allotment mid-year means either paying overage fees or losing access until renewal. Newer platforms like Apollo and Lusha offer monthly plans and pay-as-you-go pricing that reduce financial risk. For teams under 10 reps, monthly pricing almost always makes more sense than an annual commitment you might outgrow or underuse.",
 "faqs": [
 {"question": "How accurate is B2B contact data in 2026?", "answer": "Email accuracy from top providers ranges from 90-97%, with verified emails bouncing less than 5% of the time. Phone number accuracy is lower, typically 40-80% for direct dials depending on the provider. Mobile numbers are the least reliable, connecting 30-60% of the time. Always test on a sample of your target accounts before committing."},
 {"question": "What is the difference between B2B data providers and data enrichment tools?", "answer": "B2B data providers sell access to contact and company databases for prospecting. Data enrichment tools take your existing records and fill in missing fields by querying multiple sources. Some platforms like Apollo and ZoomInfo do both, but dedicated enrichment tools like Clay and Clearbit specialize in augmenting data you already have."},
 {"question": "How much do B2B data providers cost?", "answer": "Pricing ranges from free tiers with limited credits (Apollo, Lusha) to $15,000+/year for enterprise platforms like ZoomInfo. Mid-range options like Cognism and RocketReach run $3,000-$10,000/year depending on seats and credit volume. Most providers use credit-based pricing where each contact lookup costs one credit."},
 {"question": "Is it legal to use B2B contact data for cold outreach?", "answer": "In the US and most of the world, using business contact data for B2B outreach is legal under CAN-SPAM and similar regulations. GDPR in Europe requires a legitimate interest basis and an easy opt-out mechanism. Reputable providers maintain opt-out lists and compliance frameworks, but the responsibility for compliant outreach ultimately falls on your team."},
 {"question": "How often does B2B contact data go stale?", "answer": "The average American worker changes jobs every 2.7 years, so roughly 30% of contact records become outdated annually. Direct dials and mobile numbers change even faster. Top providers re-verify records every 30-90 days, but you should still expect 10-15% of any exported list to contain outdated information. Running lists through an email verification service before outreach reduces bounce rates significantly."},
 ],
}

# =============================================================================
# DATA ENRICHMENT & WORKFLOW ORCHESTRATION
# =============================================================================
CATEGORY_CONTENT["data-enrichment"] = {
 "definition": "take your existing lead and account data and fill in missing fields by querying multiple data providers in a waterfall sequence. Modern enrichment platforms combine data sourcing with workflow automation, letting revenue teams build custom prospecting and routing logic without engineering support.",
 "definition_expanded": "Data enrichment tools solve a specific problem: no single data provider has complete coverage. A waterfall approach queries Provider A first, then Provider B for any gaps, then Provider C, maximizing fill rates while minimizing cost. The category has evolved beyond simple field-filling into full workflow orchestration, where teams build automated sequences that enrich, score, route, and trigger actions across their entire tech stack.",
 "buying_guide": "The first question is whether you need basic enrichment or full workflow orchestration. If you just want to fill in missing emails and phone numbers on your CRM records, a straightforward tool like Clearbit or Dropcontact handles that well at a predictable cost. If you want to build multi-step workflows that enrich data, score leads, personalize outreach, and sync results across tools, you need a platform like Clay.\n\nWaterfall enrichment is the key feature that separates modern tools from legacy solutions. Instead of relying on one data provider, waterfall tools query multiple sources sequentially, using the cheapest or most accurate provider first and falling back to others for gaps. This approach consistently delivers 20-40% higher fill rates than any single provider alone. Ask vendors which data sources they integrate with and whether you can control the query order.\n\nPricing models vary widely. Some tools charge per enrichment credit regardless of whether data is found. Others only charge on successful matches. Clay uses a credit system where different enrichment sources cost different amounts. Clearbit charges per API call. Calculate your expected monthly volume and compare total costs across vendors. A tool that looks expensive per-credit might cost less overall if it finds data in fewer queries due to better waterfall logic.",
 "faqs": [
 {"question": "What is waterfall enrichment?", "answer": "Waterfall enrichment queries multiple data providers in sequence for each record. If the first provider returns a result, the process stops. If not, it tries the next provider, and so on. This maximizes data fill rates while keeping costs down, since cheaper or more accurate sources are queried first."},
 {"question": "How does Clay compare to Clearbit for enrichment?", "answer": "Clay is a workflow orchestration platform that integrates 50+ data providers and lets you build custom enrichment sequences. Clearbit is a focused enrichment tool that uses its own proprietary database. Clay is more powerful and flexible but has a steeper learning curve. Clearbit is simpler to implement, especially if you just need to enrich CRM records automatically."},
 {"question": "Can data enrichment tools replace my B2B data provider?", "answer": "Partially. Enrichment tools aggregate data from multiple providers, so they can replace the need for a dedicated database subscription in some cases. However, enrichment tools work best when you already have a seed list of companies or contacts to enrich. For building prospect lists from scratch, you still need a database like Apollo or ZoomInfo."},
 {"question": "What data fields can enrichment tools fill in?", "answer": "Common fields include email addresses, phone numbers, job titles, LinkedIn URLs, company revenue, headcount, industry, tech stack, funding history, and social profiles. Advanced tools can also pull intent signals, news mentions, job postings, and even estimate departmental budgets based on firmographic models."},
 {"question": "How much does data enrichment cost per record?", "answer": "Costs range from $0.01-$0.50 per record depending on the tool, the fields you need, and how many waterfall steps are involved. Email-only enrichment is cheapest. Adding phone numbers, firmographics, and intent data increases cost per record. Most platforms offer volume discounts above 10,000 records per month."},
 ],
}

# =============================================================================
# BUYER INTENT DATA
# =============================================================================
CATEGORY_CONTENT["buyer-intent"] = {
 "definition": "identify companies and buying committees that are actively researching solutions in your category. These platforms track content consumption signals, search behavior, and engagement patterns across the web to surface accounts showing purchase intent before they ever visit your website or fill out a form.",
 "definition_expanded": "Intent data comes from tracking which companies are consuming content related to specific topics at rates above their historical baseline. First-party intent captures behavior on your own properties. Third-party intent aggregates signals from thousands of B2B publisher sites, review platforms, and content networks. The signal quality varies enormously between providers, and the biggest challenge is separating genuine buying research from casual browsing or competitor employee activity.",
 "buying_guide": "Understand the difference between first-party and third-party intent data before buying. First-party intent, like tracking who visits your website or engages with your content, is high-signal but low-volume. Third-party intent, which tracks research behavior across the broader web, gives you wider coverage but noisier signals. Most effective programs combine both, using third-party data to identify accounts and first-party signals to prioritize them.\n\nSignal quality matters more than signal volume. Some vendors flag thousands of accounts per week as showing intent, which makes the data useless for prioritization. Others surface a smaller, more actionable set of accounts with stronger signals. Ask vendors to run a pilot on your target account list and measure how many flagged accounts convert to meetings or opportunities. A 30-day pilot with real conversion data is worth more than any demo.\n\nIntegration with your existing workflow is critical. Intent data sitting in a separate dashboard gets ignored within weeks. The data needs to flow directly into your CRM, sales engagement platform, or ABM tool so reps see intent signals where they already work. Ask about native integrations with Salesforce, HubSpot, Outreach, and whatever else your team uses daily. Also confirm whether the platform provides contact-level recommendations or just account-level signals, since account-level data still requires reps to figure out who to contact.",
 "faqs": [
 {"question": "How does buyer intent data work?", "answer": "Intent data providers partner with thousands of B2B publisher websites to track which companies are consuming content about specific topics. When a company researches a topic at a rate significantly above their historical baseline, the platform flags it as showing intent. The tracking typically uses IP-to-company mapping combined with cookie data and content categorization."},
 {"question": "Is buyer intent data accurate enough to act on?", "answer": "It depends on the provider and how you use it. Intent data works best as a prioritization layer on top of your existing ICP targeting. Using intent signals alone produces too many false positives. The most effective teams use intent data to prioritize outreach timing and messaging to accounts that already fit their ICP, rather than replacing their targeting criteria entirely."},
 {"question": "What is the difference between Bombora and 6sense for intent data?", "answer": "Bombora is a pure intent data provider that sells topic-level surge scores via integrations with other platforms. 6sense is a full ABM platform that includes intent data alongside predictive analytics, audience building, and advertising. Bombora is simpler and cheaper if you just want intent signals. 6sense is the choice if you want an all-in-one ABM orchestration platform."},
 {"question": "How much does buyer intent data cost?", "answer": "Standalone intent data from Bombora starts around $25,000-$40,000/year depending on topic volume and integrations. Full ABM platforms like 6sense and Demandbase range from $50,000-$200,000+/year for enterprise deployments. G2 and TrustRadius offer intent data from their review platforms at lower price points, typically $15,000-$30,000/year."},
 {"question": "Can small companies use intent data effectively?", "answer": "Intent data delivers the most value for companies with defined ICP criteria, an outbound sales motion, and enough pipeline volume to measure results. Teams with fewer than 5 reps or very niche markets often find the signal-to-noise ratio too low to justify the cost. If your total addressable market is under 5,000 accounts, the volume of intent signals may be too sparse to be actionable."},
 ],
}

